\begin_layout Standard
The process is given by 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Y_{t}=\mu_{S_{t}}+\varepsilon_{t}\label{eq:msm}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{t}$
\end_inset

 is the observed value of the time series at time 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{S_{t}}$
\end_inset

 is the intercept in state 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{t}$
\end_inset

 and
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{t}$
\end_inset

 follows a Normal distribution with mean zero and variance given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{S_{t}}^{2}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since Markov regime switching model assumes that 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{t}$
\end_inset

 follows a stochastic process that satisfied Markov property, the evolution
 of changing from state 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{t}=i$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{t}=i$
\end_inset

 is defined by the transition probabilities as follows
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
p_{ij}=P(S_{t}=j|S_{t-1}=i,S_{t-2}=k,...,S_{1}=q)=P(S_{t}=j|S_{t-1}=i)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leqslant i,j\leqslant N$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{j=1}^{N}p_{ij}=1$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:msm"

\end_inset

 is the simplest case for the switching model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Autoregressive (AR) model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Autoregressive model is one type of time series model that uses for describing
 the time-varying process.
 It is flexible in handling various kind of time series pattern.
 The name comes from how it performs a regression of the variable against
 itself or on its own previous outputs 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "cryer1986time"

\end_inset

.
 Hence, an autoressive model of order 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 or AR(p) model can be written as 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Y_{t}=c+\phi_{1}Y_{t-1}+\phi_{2}Y_{t-2}+...+\phi_{p}Y_{t-p}+\varepsilon_{t}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 is a constant and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{t}$
\end_inset

 is white noise with zero mean and variance
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $p=1$
\end_inset

, the model is called the first order autoregression process or AR(1).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Markov switching autoregressive model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is an extension of the basic Markov regime switching model (i.e., hidden
 Markov model) which also has dependencies at observation level.
 Then model relaxes the conditional independent assumption by allowing observati
on probability to also depends on the past observation and the current state
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "shannon2009formulation"

\end_inset

.
 The observations are drawn from autoregression process.
 Thus, the first order Markov switching autoregressive model is 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Y_{t}=c_{S_{t}}+\phi_{1}Y_{t-1}+\varepsilon_{t}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

